<div id="review_2005726729" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2005726729" />
    <a title="Elizabeth" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9681387-elizabeth"><img alt="Elizabeth" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1614385355p2/9681387.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2005726729?book_show_action=true">Oct 10, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elizabeth" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elizabeth" href="/user/show/9681387-elizabeth">Elizabeth</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2005726729" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18328914717176412667">The Chosen is probably one of my all time favorite books. My mom made me read it in high school (homeschooler here), I read it again for an American Lit class in college and a third time for a book club. Not many sequels are on par with the original book but this one is. Potok writes with such simplicity, such insight. Even if you know nothing about Hasidic or Orthodox Judaism or the conflicts regarding the various traditions (which I didn’t), it just sucks you in. I loved seeing how the charact</span>
  <span id="freeText18328914717176412667" style="display:none">The Chosen is probably one of my all time favorite books. My mom made me read it in high school (homeschooler here), I read it again for an American Lit class in college and a third time for a book club. Not many sequels are on par with the original book but this one is. Potok writes with such simplicity, such insight. Even if you know nothing about Hasidic or Orthodox Judaism or the conflicts regarding the various traditions (which I didn’t), it just sucks you in. I loved seeing how the characters from The Chosen continued to grow and struggle and think through what they believed. This book made me think about what a culture or faith group does in response to a shifting belief system when they have come out of a period of persecution (this book highlights the struggles of European Jews emigrating to the US after being interned in concentration camps). When you feel like the beliefs and lifestyle you suffered for are even vaguely threatened and your suffering therefore seems meaningless, what do you do? How do you respect others who think differently, how do you love them, how do you confront what you believe are truly essential threats, how do you even sort out what are real or simply perceived threats? Highly recommended.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18328914717176412667" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


