<div id="review_265797340" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/265797340" />
    <a title="Flavia Gaia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7452971-flavia-gaia"><img alt="Flavia Gaia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1327032104p2/7452971.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/265797340?book_show_action=true">Jan 21, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Flavia Gaia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Flavia Gaia" href="/user/show/7452971-flavia-gaia">Flavia Gaia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer265797340" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4635629905981694845">The Promise is a novel written by Chaim Potok and published as a sequel to The Chosen, published two years earlier. It was originally published by Alfred A. Knopf in New York. Although not quite as impressive as The Chosen, The Promise is still laudable, skillfully woven to a depth which many modern books tend to lack.<br/>The Chosen takes place in Brooklyn, New York, amongst the various Jewish sects which resided there in the 1940’s. The book begins with Reuven Malter, a Jewish student and son of pr</span>
  <span id="freeText4635629905981694845" style="display:none">The Promise is a novel written by Chaim Potok and published as a sequel to The Chosen, published two years earlier. It was originally published by Alfred A. Knopf in New York. Although not quite as impressive as The Chosen, The Promise is still laudable, skillfully woven to a depth which many modern books tend to lack.<br />The Chosen takes place in Brooklyn, New York, amongst the various Jewish sects which resided there in the 1940’s. The book begins with Reuven Malter, a Jewish student and son of prominent Talmud commentator David Malter, as 15 years old. For his entire life he has lived among the Hasidim, an extremely orthodox sect, and not known Danny Saunders, who lives 5 blocks away, and is the genius son of a Hasidic rabbi, Reb Saunders. Playing against each other in a baseball game, they meet and become friends, encouraged by David Malter. They grow together and Reuven learns of Danny’s strong wish to pass the role of rabbi onto his sickly younger brother and become a psychologist, while Reuven works toward becoming a rabbi himself. Various conflicts among Judaism, World War II, Hitler, and the Holocaust affect their lives. Danny’s religion and his father also take a toll on Reuven’s life, as he finds a deeply rooted struggle between father and son.<br />In The Promise, Reuven and Danny are both studying, Reuven for his smicha and a degree in philosophy, and Danny for a degree in psychology. They come into contact with a mentally sick boy, Michael. Michael is the son of Abraham Gordon, whose writings have caused much controversy among Jewish Talmudists. <br />Whereas the Torah is a book of law and prophecy given to Moses by God Himself, the Talmud contains the various interpretations of the Torah by ancient scholars. Therefore while it is a sacred book, it contradicts itself and is subject to emendation, and is constantly causing controversy among the modern Talmudists. <br />Reuven must work toward his smicha under a strict Rav Kalman (‘Rav’ being a title for those who have earned smicha, and are qualified to teach Talmud), who is extremely orthodox and feels that it is as much his duty to guard “the spark” as it is the Hasid’s. ‘The spark’ represents something along the lines of Yiddishkeit, or Judaism, and the ancient teachings and privilege to teach. He is against both Reuven’s father and Abraham Gordon, and Reuven still must work to earn smicha beneath him. During this, Danny is placed in charge of the treatment of Michael, and resorts to a desperate experiment in order to coerce Michael to talk in therapy. <br />The writing style is not overly descriptive, but simply tells the truth, which is what makes The Promise so successful. Certain scenes are so utterly realistic the reader is left with a hurting heart for the pain or rejoicing for the success of the characters. Also, Potok seemed to concentrate more on what happens around Reuven (as the story is told from Reuven’s point of view in first person) rather than what Reuven himself is doing; unlike some books, which are constantly sentences beginning with “I” (“I could smell this…” or “I walked there…”) This made the book not so simplistic to read, and also not so repetitive. It was interesting and very realistic. <br />While there wasn’t a lot of description per say, the descriptions were extremely realistic and artful. Again, they did not try to harangue the reader, but simply told the truth, which is what captures the reader’s attention. <br />Symbolism was prominent in this book, especially in nature. Various symbols were clouds, trees, stars, colors, and each played a secretive role in the lives of the characters. The reader is forced to question, and thus gains wisdom from the book. <br />The Jewish lives are portrayed as wonderful and challenging, and the dedication to religion astonishing to the laymen. Not only does the reader gain wisdom from the various themes, he/she also develops an appreciation for the rich religion and its ardent followers, and their mastery and dedication to scholarship. While entertaining, this book is also enlightening. <br />Chaim Potok’s The Promise masterfully illustrates the passion of Jewish scholars in America. In a seemingly simple way, it bares the truth, while intertwining classic themes and archetypes that each reader can interpret differently. Potok’s writing breaks away from the monotonous and overly descriptive pieces so highly praised today, giving the reader a new viewpoint many authors today are unable to achieve. A modern classic, The Promise will leave readers both enlightened at the wisdom and breathless at the sincerity of this piece.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="4635629905981694845" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


