<div id="review_3794730754" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3794730754" />
    <a title="Randall Kempton" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/72151786-randall-kempton"><img alt="Randall Kempton" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3794730754?book_show_action=true">Jan 31, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Randall Kempton" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Randall Kempton" href="/user/show/72151786-randall-kempton">Randall Kempton</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3794730754" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16949026575293688779">I was surprised, though I shouldn&apos;t have been, to realize suddenly how relevant this book is to our present social dilemma--the polarization between right and left, liberal and conservative. The fight is nothing new; Potok&apos;s view however, is optimistic--especially when/if we learn to see one another face to face, instead of as a constituent part of the &quot;Enemy camp&quot;. <br/>My other insight is also an optimistic one: Aren&apos;t all of our skirmishes in our various fields of endeavour just a reflection of th</span>
  <span id="freeText16949026575293688779" style="display:none">I was surprised, though I shouldn't have been, to realize suddenly how relevant this book is to our present social dilemma--the polarization between right and left, liberal and conservative. The fight is nothing new; Potok's view however, is optimistic--especially when/if we learn to see one another face to face, instead of as a constituent part of the "Enemy camp". <br />My other insight is also an optimistic one: Aren't all of our skirmishes in our various fields of endeavour just a reflection of the One battle that really matters--whether we choose God or not, or fight for the Good and True or just for ourselves? Our "opponents" in those battlefields then just seem to me to be sparring partners, allies, on the same team, just helping us hone our skills and arguments for the real battles against real evil--not Dem vs. Republican, Evangelical vs. Latter-day Saint, conservative vs. liberal--honest people in all of those battles I think all fight for the Good, but just disagree over details and means. The thing that matters may be our motivation for the battle--self-serving aggrandizement, financial gain, or power--or an honest desire to make the world better. It's changed the way I think about those battles and who I see as the real "enemy". </span>
  <a data-text-id="16949026575293688779" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

